            calculated, why accuracy matters, and how to avoid common mistakes
            when working across regions.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- HOW TIME WORKS -->
        <section id="how-time-works">
          <h2>How Current Time Is Calculated</h2>

          <p>
            At a global level, all time is based on Coordinated Universal Time
            (UTC). Each country or region applies an offset to UTC to determine
            its local time.
          </p>

          <p>
            For example, India operates at UTC+5:30, while the United Kingdom
            switches between UTC+0 and UTC+1 depending on daylight saving time.
          </p>

          <p>
            Modern time tools calculate the current time by combining UTC,
            regional time zone rules, and daylight saving schedules.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- WHY ACCURACY -->
        <section id="why-accuracy">
          <h2>Why Accuracy Matters More Than You Think</h2>

          <p>
            A difference of even one hour can cause missed meetings, delayed
            responses, and scheduling conflicts. For businesses, these small
            errors compound quickly.
          </p>

          <p>
            Accuracy is especially important for:
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Scheduling meetings across time zones</li>
            <li>Booking travel or interviews</li>
            <li>Running automated systems or cron jobs</li>
            <li>Managing global customer support</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- CITY VS COUNTRY -->
        <section id="city-vs-country">
          <h2>Country vs City Time Differences</h2>

          <p>
            Some countries span multiple time zones. This means “current time in
            a country” is not always a single value.
          </p>

          <p>
            For example, the United States, Russia, and Australia all have
            multiple time zones. In these cases, checking the current time by
            city is far more accurate than relying on country-level time.
          </p>

          <p>
            A
            <a href="/world-clock/">World Clock (Professional)</a>
            allows you to track multiple cities simultaneously and avoid
            confusion.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- COMMON MISTAKES -->
        <section id="common-mistakes">
          <h2>Common Mistakes When Checking Current Time</h2>

          <p>
            Many people rely on memory, static charts, or outdated sources when
            checking time across regions. These approaches fail during daylight
            saving changes or political time zone updates.
          </p>

          <ul>
            <li>Assuming time differences never change</li>
            <li>Ignoring daylight saving time</li>
            <li>Using country-level time for multi-zone countries</li>
            <li>Relying on cached or outdated data</li>
          </ul>
